[1] UKHSA
Date: Fri 17 Jun 2022
Source: UK Health Security Agency (HSA) [edited]
https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/acute-hepatitis-technical-briefing/investigation-into-acute-hepatitis-of-unknown-aetiology-in-children-in-england-case-update


This is an epidemiological briefing produced to share data useful to other public health investigators. Full technical briefings will continue to be produced when appropriate. For the purposes of this summary, cases refer to confirmed (10 years old and under) and possible (11 to 15 year old) cases -- see case definition in Technical Briefing 3 (https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/acute-hepatitis-technical-briefing). The public health agencies of the 4 nations continue to work with the NHS [National Health Service] to classify reported case-patients who have incomplete laboratory information (referred to as "pending").

Cases in the UK
--------------
As of 13 Jun 2022, there are 260 cases (251 confirmed and 9 possible) cases of acute non-A-E hepatitis with serum transaminases greater than 500 IU/L identified in children aged under 16 years old in the UK, since 1 Jan 2022. Of these, 187 cases (180 confirmed and 7 possible) are resident in England, 32 (all confirmed) in Scotland, 17 (all confirmed) in Wales and 24 (22 confirmed and 2 possible) in Northern Ireland (Figure 1 [see below]). This is the result of an active case-finding investigation starting in April 2022 which identified retrospective as well as prospective cases.

Between 21 Jan 2022 and 13 Jun 2022, 12 children in the UK meeting the case definition have required liver transplantation; no cases resident in the UK have died.

While new cases continue to be identified across the UK, there is an overall decline in the number of new cases reported per week, even allowing for reporting lags. Cases pending classification are usually those in which laboratory testing to rule out known causes of hepatitis has not been completed.

Figure 1. Cases by week of presentation, 1 Jan to 13 Jun 2022
