Source: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) [edited]
https://www.cdc.gov/ncird/investigation/hepatitis-unknown-cause/updates.html


Persons under investigation: children with acute hepatitis of unknown etiology
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
While rare, children can still have serious hepatitis, and we do not always know the cause. That is why investigators continue to look at possible causes and investigate.

Numbers of persons under investigation (PUI): 290

PUI does not mean this person is a confirmed case. The states and CDC are looking broadly (including hepatitis cases of unknown origin in children under 10 years of age, since October 2021), so this number may go up or down as CDC and states review medical charts and learn more.

States and jurisdictions reporting at least one person under investigation (41)* as of 15 Jun 2022
(*These may not be recent cases of hepatitis being reported.) [see source URL for map and data table].

States or territories with no reported PUI (all others have possible cases but no numbers given) as "To protect patient privacy, numbers for each state will not be released.": Alaska, American Samoa, District of Columbia, Guam, Iowa, Kansas, Marshall Islands, Micronesia, Montana, New Hampshire, North Marianas, Oregon, Palau, South Carolina, Vermont, Virgin Islands, West Virginia, Wyoming.

These data were posted on 15 Jun 2022 and reflect data from 1 Oct 2021. Reported PUIs are preliminary and subject to change as more data become available. Data will be updated weekly.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[No epicurve or anything like it has been reported for the US data, nor are there substantial data regarding present or past SARS-CoV-2 infection in American children affected. Although CDC is not releasing individual state numbers "to protect patient privacy," individual state numbers do come out. Numbers per state are published by CDC for other infections such as the US nationwide hepatitis A virus outbreak. The etiology or etiologies of this seeming increase in severe liver inflammation remain unclear, although adenovirus and SARS-CoV-2 remain in the equation, separately or together. - Mod.LL

